      "(t * x)| = Real.exp (t * x) ≤ Real.exp (t * (μ + 2 * √v)) ≤ Real.exp (|t| * (|μ| + 2 * √v))`.\n     Similarly, if `t < 0`, then `|t * x| = (-t) * x ≤ (-t) * (μ + 2 * √v)` if `x ≥ 0`, etc. This is getting complicated, and it's not clear how to always get the intended upper bound.\n\n   But perhaps it's not needed at all. \n\n- **Step 2 (c012)**: This is straightforward because `Real.exp (t * x)` is continuous, hence `volume`-integrable on any compact set. But in Lean, it might require some setup. If the previous step had `S` being compact, perhaps we could use something like `Continuous.integrableOn_Icc`.\n\n   However, the issue is that in Lean, `t : ℝ` is arbitrary, so `Real.exp (t * x)` is not necessarily integrable over all `ℝ` unless we restrict to compact sets. \n\n   However, since `c012` is marked as `sorry`, perhaps it was intended that `c012` is not used in the proof. \n\n- **Step 3 (c013)**: If `S` were compact, this would be straightforward given `c011`, but again, `c011` is a suspect statement.\n\n   Alternatively, perhaps we don't need `c011` and `c013`, and `c012` can be used to directly deduce the integral is finite. \n\n   However, the actual semicircle measure is not the same as the volume measure (`ProbabilityTheory.semicircleReal μ v` is `volume` with a density).\n\n   But in Lean, there seems to be no immediate implication from `volume`-integrability to `ProbabilityTheory.semicircleReal μ v`-integrability, as far as I can tell from the earlier code. \n\n   Alternatively, perhaps the function is bounded on `S`, and we can use the fact that the semicircle measure is supported on `S`, but in Lean this needs more work.\n\n- **Step 4 (c014)**: It seems that we don't actually need `c011`, `c012`, or `c013` if we instead consider that `Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded on the support of the semicircle measure (which is `S`). \n\n   Indeed, the semicircle measure has support contained in `S`, so to check integrability against it, it's sufficient to check that `Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded on `S`. \n\n   Let's try to use this approach instead. \n\n   - Since `x ∈ S`, we have `x ∈ [μ - 2 * √v, μ + 2 * √v]`, so `|t * x| ≤ |t| * (|μ| + 2 * √v)` because:\n     - For any real `a, b`, `|a + b| ≤ |a| + |b|`, so `x = μ - 2 * √v ≤ μ + 2 * √v`, and thus `|x| ≤ |μ| + 2 * √v`.\n   - Therefore, `Real.exp (t * x) ≤ Real.exp (|t| * (|μ| + 2 * √v))` when `t * x ≥ 0`, but `Real.exp (t * x)` can be large when `t * x < 0` (e.g., `t = -1`, `x = μ + 2 * √v`). Hmm, that was incorrect.\n\n   No! Actually, since `x ∈ [μ - 2 * √v, μ + 2 * √v]`, then:\n   - `t * x` ranges between `t * (μ - 2 * √v)` and `t * (μ + 2 * √v)` if `t ≥ 0`, or the other way around if `t ≤ 0`. \n   - The maximum of `Real.exp (t * x)` on this interval will be at either endpoint `x = μ - 2 * √v` or `x = μ + 2 * √v`. \n   - Specifically, if `t > 0`, then `Real.exp (t * x)` is increasing in `x`, so its maximum is `Real.exp (t * (μ + 2 * √v))`.\n   - If `t < 0`, then `Real.exp (t * x)` is decreasing in `x`, so its maximum is `Real.exp (t * (μ - 2 * √v))`.\n   - But `Real.exp (t * (μ + 2 * √v)) = Real.exp (t * μ + 2 * √v * t)`, and `Real.exp (t * (μ - 2 * √v)) = Real.exp (t * μ - 2 * √v * t)`.\n\n   To find a uniform upper bound, perhaps we can consider:\n   - If `t ≥ 0`, then `Real.exp (t * x) ≤ Real.exp (t * (μ + 2 * √v)) = Real.exp (t * μ + 2 * t * √v) ≤ Real.exp (|t| * (|μ| + 2 * √v))` because `t * μ ≤ |t| * |μ|`.\n   - Similarly, if `t ≤ 0`, then `Real.exp (t * x) ≤ Real.exp (t * (μ - 2 * √v)) = Real.exp (t * μ - 2 * t * √v)`, but since `t ≤ 0`, `-2 * t * √v = 2 * |t| * √v`, and `t * μ ≤ |t| * |μ|`, so again `Real.exp (t * x) ≤ Real.exp (|t| * (|μ| + 2 * √v))`.\n\n   This gives us that for all `x ∈ S`, `Real.exp (t * x) ≤ Real.exp (|t| * (|μ| + 2 * √v))`. \n   Since `Real.exp (t * x) > 0`, we have `|Real.exp (t * x)| ≤ Real.exp (|t| * (|μ| + 2 * √v))` as well. \n\n   Therefore, `c011` was correct except that it should not have the absolute value on the LHS (but since `Real.exp` is always positive, it doesn't matter).\n\n   Hence, `c011` is not necessarily incorrect but needs to be adjusted.\n\nBut since `c011` is already marked as `sorry`, perhaps the real issue is that the proof sketch is incomplete.\n\nHere is an alternative sketch of the proof:\n1. The function `x ↦ Real.exp (t * x)` is continuous.\n2. The semicircle measure has compact support (equal to `S`).\n3. Continuous functions on compact sets are bounded, hence integrable against any finite measure. \n\nBut Lean's `ProbabilityTheory.semicircleReal` is not yet proven to have support `S`, and we might need to prove this first. \n\nAlternatively:\n1. `x ↦ Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded on `S`, because `S` is compact and the function is continuous.\n2. The measure `ProbabilityTheory.semicircleReal μ v` is finitely supported (in fact, has total mass `1`). \n3. Therefore, the integral of a bounded function against a finite measure is finite. \n\nBut we need to formalize that `S` is compact (which it is because it's closed and bounded in `ℝ`) and that the measure is supported on `S`. \n\nHowever, in Lean, it seems that to get integrability of a function `f` against a measure `m`, we need to either:\n- Show that `f` is integrable in the usual sense (i.e., `∫ |f| < ∞`) and `m` is `volume`, or \n- Use some other property. \n\nIt seems that the previous approach tried to use the fact that `volume` integrates `f`, but it's not directly useful because `m` is not `volume`. \n\nAlternatively, if we could show that `m` is absolutely continuous with respect to `volume`, and the density is bounded, then we could rely on `volume`'s integrability. \n\nBut `m = semicircleReal μ v` has density `semicirclePDF μ v`, which is bounded (as it's `1 / (2 * π * v) * sqrt(...)` and `sqrt(...) ≤ 2 * sqrt(v)`). \n\nTherefore, perhaps we can show that `Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded on the support of `m`, and since the support is compact, it is integrable.\n\nBut perhaps it's better to proceed in Lean by directly proving that:\n1. `Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded on `S`, because it is continuous and `S` is compact. \n2. The measure `m` has support `S`, hence its total mass is `1`.\n3. Therefore, the integral of `Real.exp (t * x)` against `m` is finite. \n\nBut Lean doesn't yet know that `m` has support `S` unless we prove it. \n\nAlternatively, perhaps we can do the following:\n1. Since `m` has support contained in `S`, we can consider integrating `Real.exp (t * x)` on `S`.\n2. The function is bounded on `S`, so the integral is finite. \n\nIn Lean, this would be done by noting that `m` is `volume` with a bounded density, and `Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded on `S`. \n\nBut perhaps it's easier to instead note that `Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded by some constant `C` on `S`, and then `∫ Real.exp (t * x) d m ≤ C * m(S) = C * 1 = C < ∞`.\n\nSo we don't need `volume` at all in this approach.\n\nLet me try to formalize this:\n\n### Revised Approach\n\n1. Show that `Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded on the support of `m`, which is `S`. \n   - Actually, Lean knows that the support of `m` is `S` from the earlier result (the first `have` statement in the proof).\n   - But perhaps we can instead directly use that `Real.exp (t * x)` is bounded on `S` (`S` is compact).\n   - Therefore, there exists `C > 0` such that for all `x ∈ S`, `Real.exp (t * x) ≤ C`.\n2. The measure `m` is concentrated",
